description.plain:
Founded back in 1996 after the separation of Kyuss, Josh Homme embarked upon a mission to bring Desert Rock to the frontier of music.

Since their creation, they have gone through various line-ups and more musical styles and moods, ranging from electronic robot rock (Era Vulgaris), dark and sexy (Lullabies to Paralyze), cathartic, (…Like Clockwork) and robotic dance rock with their 2017 release (Villains).

Throughout the years, their lineup has included many notable musicians, including Mark Lanegan and Dave Grohl.

description.plain:
“3’s and 7’s” was released as the second single off of Era Vulgaris. Despite the misleading name, skittish guitar and erratic tempo changes, this song is actually in a run-of-the-mill 4/4 time signature until the coda.

During an acoustic set, Homme stated that it was a song about lying.

The band performed the song during Popworld 2007, but instead of using instruments, they used laptops while Josh sang, in a tongue-in-cheek commentary about the then-rise of technology in music. It was very reminiscent of the band Kraftwerk’s style of musical performance.

description.plain:
This song has bassist Nick Oliveri singing the lead vocals for this song. This fact becomes disturbing when you find one of the reasons why he left Queens of the Stone Age.

“In January 2004, following a string of dates touring in Australia, Oliveri was fired from the band, with reasoning at first being aggressive treatment of the band’s fans, later being accusations of possible abuse to his girlfriend. Oliveri has said to have come to the conclusion himself that during a sound check at a show in Spain in 2003 he acted too aggressively to Josh Homme over his relationship with then-girlfriend Brody Dalle after getting too drunk on wine, raising tension between the two."

songs.title: A Song for the Dead

description.plain:
One of the most kickass songs on the album, “A Song for the Dead” hits you like a freight train with its heavy, simplistic guitar riffs and dark, brooding vocals. Classic Queens of the Stone Age at its best.
In 2014, Ultimate Guitar users voted the song as the best Queens of the Stone Age song of their discography. Featuring hard-hitting drums by Dave Grohl (a drum part which has since been regarded as one of the best of all time), a haunting vocal by Mark Lanegan of the Screaming Trees, and brick-heavy guitars that develop into a jam-type solo, which is impossible not to headbang to, it’s hard to disagree with UG users.

description.plain:
Thematically, the song follows the fairytale inspired theme of Lullabies To Paralyze. The song describes a witch trial and the fact that people accused of being witches had done nothing and were wrongly killed. This is pretty congruent with history. Events like the Salem Witch Trials, which was caused by mass hysteria, seem to be the topic of this song. The personal twist behind the song is that Josh Homme felt victimized in a similar way because of the flak he received for sacking his longtime friend, bassist, vocalist, and co-songwriter Nick Oliveri in between this album and their last, Songs for the Deaf.

“Burn The Witch” was released as the fourth and final single off of Lullabies to Paralyze. The song features Billy Gibbons of ZZ Top on vocals and guitar.

description.plain:
“Domesticated Animals” spins around a 7/8 time signature, a lowkey simplistic guitar riff and a heavy bassline that slowly builds in momentum until it erupts during the song’s mid section.



Lyrically, the song alludes to social “groupthink,” when mass consensus, a lack of creativity and personal responsibility combine. Josh speaks out against conformity, championing the individual mind and standing as a singular voice outside the many.

In artwork drawn by artist Boneface, this song was originally entitled “Where The Gold Is?”

description.plain:
The Latin term “Era Vulgaris” actually translates to ‘Common Era’, instead of ‘Vulgar Era’ as one might guess. Josh Homme chose it because “It sounds like ‘the Vulgar Era’, which I like, because that sounds like something that I would like to be part of.”

The titular song was not included on the US standard version of the album. Initially, it was released only to winners of a contest held on the fansite thefade.net and sent to the winners on a CD entitled “You Know What You Did”.



Era Vulgaris was later officially released on the Australia, New Zealand, and UK standard editions of the album, as track number 13.

description.plain:
Described as “a social experiment” by QOTSA frontman Josh Homme, this song is a semi-satirical swipe at the dying and derided genre of stoner rock within which Homme had made his name.

The song title is a play on words, as a “hit” means a popular song, but can also refer to drug use (i.e., to take a hit from a joint or a bong).

According to producer Christopher Goss, the song was originally conceived as a chant and a “joke song” to tack onto the end of the album. It seems highly likely that the reprise of this song was the first to be written, with the full song being developed later on.

songs.full_title: Feet Don't Fail Me by Queens of the Stone Age
songs.title: Feet Don’t Fail Me

description.plain:
Opening Villains with a slow-paced eerily build-up that lasts for almost half the length of your average pop song, “Feet Don’t Fail Me,” eventually kicks the door in with a thumping uptempo metallic groove.



The song marked the comeback of Queens of the Stone Age as it was the first official snippet of a new song since 2013’s … Like Clockwork.

Homme explained that most of the song was influenced by the Lakota Sioux powwow that he listened to when touring with Iggy Pop before they went on-stage. He also revealed that the second half of the song was something he brought to the Post Pop Depression sessions, but which was never worked on and thus did not make it into that album.

songs.full_title: Fortress by Queens of the Stone Age
songs.title: Fortress

description.plain:
The introductory violins of “Fortress” marks Villains‘ first ballad, though the heartfelt emotions slowly evolve into a heavy guitar-laden finish.

Josh spoke about creating “Fortress” to Rolling Stone Magazine. Although he doesn’t reveal what specifically inspired the song, he says he feels good about showing his true self more on this album.

When you’re younger, I think you are encouraged or you encourage yourself to hide behind a mask. As the years have gone on, that mask has worn away. I’ve lost any reason to hide. I have a vast disinterest in hiding anything when it comes to writing music. The more vulnerable and honest it is, the better I feel about it.

In an interview in The Wall Street Journal in August 2017, it was revealed that Boneface drew a young girl draped in her father’s leather jacket and contemplating a key, as imagery for the song.

songs.full_title: Gonna Leave You by Queens of the Stone Age
songs.title: Gonna Leave You

description.plain:
“Gonna Leave You” is sung by Nick Oliveri, the bassist of Queens of the Stone Age on their second and third albums.

Lyrically, “Gonna Leave You” has overlap with “Leg of Lamb” which contains the lines: “In a hotel on the phone/You’re gonna leave me, I should’ve known.”

It may also be an allusion to Led Zeppelin’s “Babe I’m Gonna Leave You.”  Queens have done this before; the song from the first album “You Can’t Quit Me Baby” is likely a reference to Zeppelin’s “I Can’t Quit You Baby.”

“Gonna Leave You” might be treated as a follow-up to “Leg of Lamb”, told from the other side of the relationship.

songs.full_title: Hideaway by Queens of the Stone Age
songs.title: Hideaway

description.plain:
Studded with synths and a slow, sexy groove, “Hideaway”’s lyrics suggest a romantic entanglement between predator and prey. Allusions are made that the relationship is not equal, full of psychological manipulation, and is in essence hidden from view.



The image drawn by Boneface is that of an iron maiden, a circa-14th century torture device of Germanic origin. This “Eiserne Jungfrau” depicted has a coin box to trigger operation (like that of a coin-operated kiddie ride, though those are usually horses, cars, or spaceships) and the grotesque face is painted with red circles on the cheeks and red lips, akin to a clown. It is covered with stickers, sayings and admonishments. “I’ve had the time of my life and I’ve never felt this way before,” written on a white banner that wraps around the middle of the iron maiden, invokes the theme song of the 1987 film Dirty Dancing. If one were to ride this “ride,” it would certainly be the last time of your life. An iron maiden does not willingly let go of its victim, trapping them inside and impaling the victim on its spike-covered interior, which speaks to the themes of the song’s lyrics of “entangling prey” forever.

While never released as a single, the visual artist Boneface collaborated with QotSA and made a short animation for this, as well as several other songs from the album.

songs.full_title: Kalopsia by Queens of the Stone Age
songs.title: Kalopsia

description.plain:
The beautifully dark elements of this album come into play as Kalopsia begins. It’s start is very slow and interesting, and provides a nice break from the nonstop rocking up to that point.
“Kalopsia” is also a defined delusion: it’s when people think what they’re seeing is more beautiful than it actually is. The song was written to Josh’s daughters and is about escaping dark days.



The inspiration for the song came from Josh Homme’s friend and fellow lyricist Arctic Monkey’s Alex Turner, with whom he occasionally exchanges words or phrases for lyric ideas. During the making of the album, Homme asked Turner to send him a word to which he replied with a text message containing the word “Kalopsia” and its definition. In an interview from 2013 Homme stated:

He kinda just didn’t know how much he’d hit the nail on the head for where I was at at the time.

Despite not being released as a single, the visual artist Boneface created a short animation for the song.

songs.full_title: Leg of Lamb by Queens of the Stone Age
songs.title: Leg of Lamb

description.plain:
Josh once said that this song was relative to other songs by Queens Of The Stone Age, which proves true: you can hear heavy traces of “Medication” from Lullabies to Paralyze, as well as traces of “I’m Designer”, in the song.



When asked whether his lyrics and music tended toward a strict expression of a certain tale or an overflow of powerful feelings in a particular moment, Josh said:

I love to paint a picture more than anything else. I like the imagery side [of music], which is really all that there is to storytelling. I hate the path of language, and when someone says, [sings lyrics by Stained] ‘It’s been a while,’ all of that is too colorless to me; although, I’m having trouble being colorful right now. I’d rather have something like ‘Leg of Lamb’ where I can picture it: ‘I don’t want to be some hanging leg of lamb’ [static, motionless, dead], and instantly, I can see what that means. For me, lyrically, it’s got to be real or it isn’t. It needs to be something that has happened or something that I have seen or that I have had a little experience with. Otherwise, it doesn’t mean anything to me.

songs.title: Long Slow Goodbye

description.plain:
The lyrics to “Long Slow Goodbye” should be read in conjunction with the lyrics to the album’s opening track, “This Lullaby,” which together may be seen to bookend the album.

In each song, Homme questions the whereabouts of an absent loved one, who may be presumed either missing, deceased, or has decided to move on from their relationship with Homme. It is not explicitly clear.
The lyrics of “Long Slow Goodbye” are decidedly more mournful and suggest that the author’s quest to find a missing loved one has been fruitless. However, Homme continues to question their whereabouts, wait by the telephone and lose sleep over them. This suggests they are not dead and that not all hope is lost.

In September 2018, CNN used “Long Slow Goodbye” in ads for the final episodes of the deceased Anthony Bourdain’s show. Homme recorded the theme song to Bourdain’s show and they were friends in real life. Homme played the song on the Villains Tour and dedicated it to Bourdain.

description.plain: One of the sexiest rock songs of the 21st Century, “Make It Wit Chu” was released as the third and last single of the album. Upon its release, many hardcore QotSA fans felt that the song was a departure from the otherwise hard-hitting sound that was QotSA’s trademark. They felt this song was made to get a foot inside of “MTV-land.” However, the song was written because Homme had met and fallen in love with his then-to-be wife Brody Dalle just prior to the Dessert Sessions recordings The Desert Sessions Vol. 9 & 10 that spawned the song. Originally it was named “I Wanna Make It Wit Chu.”

description.plain: Six Shooter, like the rest of the tracks on Songs for the Deaf, fits into a loose concept album about a drive from Los Angeles to the Joshua Tree and the various radio stations encountered along the way. In this case, the song is on a death metal station, and is accordingly the heaviest and most scream-heavy track on the album. Bassist Nick Oliveri sings on this song with his signature angry, screaming vocals which can be heard on other songs such as Quick and to the Pointless, You Think I Ain’t Worth a Dollar…, and Tension Head.

songs.full_title: The Evil Has Landed by Queens of the Stone Age
songs.title: The Evil Has Landed

description.plain:
With a Led Zeppelin-esque guitar riff and a testosterone fueled outro, the epic “The Evil Has Landed” marks a last highlight on the record before the closing track.

It was released as the second single off of Villains August 10th 2017.



The imagery drawn by Boneface for the deluxe edition of the LP vinyl features a devil puppet with the “shattered Q” logo on its chest, held aloft by an hand/arm wrapped in bandages. The style of the devil puppet is reminiscent of Punch and Judy, a traditional puppet show that typically takes a violent turn, commonly associated with British seaside culture.

The title may be a play of the phrase “the eagle has landed,” spoken by astronaut Neil Armstrong when he landed on the moon. The line was meant to indicate that a mission objective was completed.

In an interview with WDR 1LIVE Homme revealed that the introductory riff was something he had had in his head for 15 years.

songs.title_with_featured: The Fun Machine Took a Shit & Died

description.plain:
“The Fun Machine Took a Shit & Died” was released as a promotional single off of Era Vulgaris. It was not included in the original version of the album, but made its way onto various regional/expanded editions of it. It was originally intended to be on the band’s fourth studio album, Lullabies To Paralyze. Josh Homme explained that this was due to the tapes getting lost:

The tapes got lost. Actually, they were just at another studio, but we falsely accused everyone in the world of theft.

The peculiar title of the song stems from a keyboard QotSA used at their Ranch de la luna studio, nicknamed “the fun machine”, which broke down.

The fun machine had a quick cameo in one of the promotional videos of QotSA’s 2017 album, Villains.

songs.full_title: Villains of Circumstance by Queens of the Stone Age
songs.title: Villains of Circumstance

description.plain:
The closing track of the album, “Villains Of Circumstance” was actually written years before its release, as it has been performed as far back as 2014. The song is a long slow paced ballad akin to “The Vampyre of Time and Memory” off the previous album …Like Clockwork, although VoC features an uptempo and uplifting chorus.



The imagery drawn by Boneface for the song features a severed hand, its digits melting into dripping wax as the flames flicker where the nails once were, with red string wrapped around the index and pinkie fingers forming a ‘V’ over the top of the wrist. Starting with the hand itself: this could be what is known as a Hand of Glory, the dried and pickled hand of a hanged man (indeed a “villain”), usually the left hand (as depicted) that when prepared properly and lighted, would render those to whom it was presented motionless or frozen. The red string could be representative of the red thread of fate, an Eastern Asian belief derived from legend, that in some myths depicts a red string tied around the pinkie or little finger that binds those who are destined to meet and/or help each other.

Taking this into context of the lyrics and what Josh has said in interviews about the song being written as a legacy as well as for his children, it’s easy to interpret that the candle-like hand is a light in the darkness guiding his loved ones to this moment in time when he recorded a message of love, the red string binding them across the (physical and metaphorical) distance that separates them.

A teaser video featuring parts of the song was released by the band on August 14th 2017.

description.plain:
The persona sings in second person about a “psycho” obsession he/she (just referred to he/him from here on out, but a gender is not explicitly given in the song) has with someone. The lyrics depict such a strong obsession that the persona cuts himself and eventually commits suicide to ensure he’ll be on her mind forever. Finally, the repeated outro of “You’re solid gold, I’ll see you in hell” is likely inferring that despite the perfection he sees in her, he’ll eventually drag her down to hell with him.

The title of the song could be a possible reference to the Led Zeppelin track, “I Can’t Quit You Baby.”

description.plain:
The opening track on Queens of the Stone Age’s third (and arguably most famous) album, Songs for the Deaf. The song begins with the sound of a car starting and a radio turning on, which introduces the use of short radio segments between the album’s songs to tell a loose story about driving from Los Angeles out into the California high desert. The song consists of bassist Nick Oliveri’s screamed vocals over churning guitars and intense drumming from Gene Trautmann.

The song was originally written by Mario Lalli, a member of the Desert Sessions.
